br_data <- fread(filename)

br_data <- br_data %>% 
  select(reg = regiao, st = estado, mun = municipio, date = data, 
         pop = populacaoTCU2019, cases_accum = casosAcumulado, 
         cases_new = casosNovos, deaths_accum = obitosAcumulado, 
         deaths_new = obitosNovos) %>% 
  mutate(pop = as.numeric(pop)) %>%  # make pop numeric
  mutate(date_d = as.Date(date, format = "%m/%d/%Y")) # put dates in calculable 

# Clean region and state names

br_data <- br_data %>% 
  left_join(state_names, by = c("st" = "sigla"))

Apparent Reclassification of Cases and Deaths away from COVID-19

As can be seen, there are two issues with the data. Both cases_new and deaths_new have negative values for the minimum value. This must mean that the Ministry has reclassified some cases and deaths as not being related to COVID-19. Next, I will create a table of those days and geographic regions that registered these negative values to see if a pattern exists.

neg_mins <- br_data %>% 
  filter(cases_new < 0 | deaths_new < 0) %>% 
  select(reg, st, state_name, mun, date, cases_new, deaths_new)
glimpse(neg_mins)

st_neg_vals <- unique(neg_mins$state_name)

All the states, except for the Distrito Federal, have these negative values: Rondnia, Acre, Amazonas, Roraima, Par, Amap, Tocantins, Maranho, Piau, Cear, Rio Grande do Norte, Paraba, Pernambuco, Alagoas, Sergipe, Bahia, Minas Gerais, Esprito Santo, Rio de Janeiro, So Paulo, Paran, Santa Catarina, Rio Grande do Sul, Mato Grosso do Sul, Mato Grosso, Gois.

We will look to see if they are concentrated in specific dates.

# use summarize to count the number of negative values per given date to find a pattern?
# need to filter out state only numbers (is.na(mun)) to avoid double counting
date_neg_vals <- neg_mins %>% 
  filter(!is.na(mun)) %>% 
  group_by(date) %>% 
  summarise(negs_by_date = n()) %>% 
  ungroup() 

# Make a bar chart to see if there is a pattern to when these negative values occur

gr_neg_mins <- date_neg_vals %>%

         y = "negs_by_date",

Inconsistency in Reporting of Cases and Deaths at State Level

When we accumulate the data to get state totals for any given date, there has appeared another inconsistency that the Ministry has not addressed and could be causing a further undercount of cases and deaths. The standard data format for the file includes a field for population, as noted above. The standard way the file gives a statewide total for a given day is to leave the municipality field (mun) blank, i.e., with the missing data valueNA. So, for June, the statewide values for Alagoas appear in the following record:

br_data %>% 
  filter(st == "AL" & date == "6/21/2020" & mun == "") %>% 
  select(st, mun, date:deaths_new) %>% 
  kable(caption = "Data for June for Alagoas (AL)")
Data for June for Alagoas (AL)
st mun date pop cases_accum cases_new deaths_accum deaths_new
AL 6/21/2020 3337357 28657 959 884 18
AL 6/21/2020 NA 91 3 6 0

These values in the table for the most recent date (6/21/20) tally with the values published for Alagoas on that day as shown on the MoS COVID-19 site only for the line that shows a non-zero population for the state.

MoS Site, Alagoas June 11

However, there is a second line that meets the search requirement for statewide data, but with the population value missing.

br_data %>% 
  filter(st == "AL" & date == "6/21/2020" & mun == "" & is.na(pop)) %>% 
  select(st, mun, date:deaths_new)

It is not at all clear what the 91 total cases and 6 total deaths on this line refer to. If it were to a municipality, that field would have a value. If it is statewide, then why is it not included in the first line? The lack of a population value in the case of some municipalities makes sense as the government may not have an accurate value for population. However, when considering the statewide total, the lack of population value does not make sense since it was used in the previous line.

More important, these cases in the second line are not included in the statewide totals that the Ministry uses. This could be a programming mistake when generating the table. Whatever the reason, it is not clear whether these 91 cases in Alagoas are an undercount that should have been included in the statewide number of cases.

miss_pop_cases <- br_data %>% filter(is.na(pop) & reg != "Brasil" & mun == "")
miss_pop_states <- length(unique(miss_pop_cases$st))
miss_pop_tot <- nrow(miss_pop_cases)

Similar unclear and unexplained missing population data lines of the database occur as early as March 28. Throughout the database, the problem occurs 1827 times up to and including June 11 and affects all 21. This includes Rio de Janeiro and So Paulo, the states with the two highest number of cases and deaths.

To remain consistent with the state and regional totals in the MoS published totals, I will also not include these cases until the government makes clear what they refer to and whether they should be included in the totals.

Comparison of Brazil with Other Countries

Comparison Based on Counts of Confirmed Cases and Deaths

I will compare Brazils evolution of COVID-19 with a series of countries which are at various stages of the pandemic curve relative to Brazil. I will do this with data from the same day, June 11, that I have been using. The international data comes from the Johns Hopkins University repository and dashboard generally accepted as the most complete and well-curated repository of COVID-19 data.1

covid_jhu <- readRDS(here("data", "covid_data_2020-06-22.rds"))

countries_interest <- c("Brazil", "Germany", "Mexico", "Peru", "UK", "US")

interest <- covid_jhu %>% 
  # shorten name of UK
  mutate(country = ifelse(country == "United Kingdom", "UK", country)) %>% 
  filter(country %in% countries_interest) %>% 
  group_by(date, country) %>% 
  summarise(cases = sum(cases),
            deaths = sum(deaths)) %>% 

  ungroup()

## Confirmed Cases for Countries of Interest 

gr_interest <- interest %>% 
  select(country, date, cases) %>% 
  filter(date > "2020/02/28") %>% 
  mutate(country = fct_drop(country)) %>% 
  ggline(x = "date",
         y = "cases",
         group = "country",
         color = "country",
         plot_type = "l",
         palette = "aaas",

  scale_y_log10()

# print patchwork graphs
gr_interest + gr_interest_d +
  plot_annotation("COVID-19 Cases & Deaths")

Two disturbing trends appear in the above graphs. First, although Brazil started its rise in both the number of confirmed cases and deaths later than the United States, it has risen rapidly to become the country with the second-most cases and deaths (having surpassed the UK in the past two days). Brazils trajectory is still rising rather than stabilizing. The second disturbing trend is that all three Latin American countries in this list are the three whose growth in deaths and confirmed cases is still accelerating rather than leveling off.

These trends can be seen in a comparison of the daily increase in deaths among these six countries.

gr_di_c_int

Here, the rising trend of Brazil, Mexico and Peru in relation to Germany, the United Kingdom and the United States. Brazil, the United Kingdom and the United States show increases in excess of 1,000 deaths per day since March. However, the United Kingdoms number of daily deaths has since declined to 300 per day although both Brazil and the United States daily deaths remain higher than any other country. Alongside this, both Mexico and Peru join Brazil in having deaths still increasing day to day. This suggests that the initial epidemic in all three countries will continue and calls into question economic opening measures in all three countries until this trend is reversed and begins to decline.

Comparison of Confirmed Cases and Deaths Accounting for Population

Comparing countries based on raw counts of deaths and cases does not provide a totally fair comparison. These are countries of vastly different geographic sizes and populations. The following figure shows how these countries compare when the relative population of each country is taken into account. For population, I will use the World Banks population estimates for 2018 and I will create a new variable: cases or deaths per 100,000 population.

# Get the World Bank population data from API_SP.POP.TOTL_DS2_en_csv_v2_887275.csv from the 
# World Bank data website; adjust "United Kingdom" to "UK"

pop <- read_csv(glue(here(), "/data/total_pop_world_bank.csv"), col_names = FALSE, skip = 5) %>% 
  select(country = X1, pop2018 = X63) %>% 
  mutate(country = ifelse(country == "United Kingdom", "UK", country),
         country = ifelse(country == "United States", "US", country))

interest <- interest %>% 
  left_join(pop, by = "country") %>% 
  mutate(country = factor(country),
         cases_Mpop = cases * 100000 / pop2018, 
         deaths_Mpop = deaths * 100000 / pop2018) 

## Redo graph

g_conf_pop <- interest %>% 
  select(country, date, cases_Mpop) %>% 
  filter(date > "2020/03/01") %>% 
  ggline(x = "date",
         y = "cases_Mpop",
         group = "country",
         color = "country",
         plot_type = "l",
         palette = "uchicago", 
         title = "Confirmed Cases",
         xlab = FALSE,
         ylab = "Number per 100,000 Pop",
         legend = "none",
         repel = TRUE,
         show.line.label = TRUE,
         ggtheme = theme_gray()) +
  scale_x_date(date_breaks = "21 days", date_labels = "%m/%d") +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 1000, 100))


g_death_pop <- interest %>% 
  select(country, date, deaths_Mpop) %>% 
  filter(date > "2020/03/01") %>% 
  ggline(x = "date",
         y = "deaths_Mpop",
         group = "country",
         color = "country",
         plot_type = "l",
         palette = "uchicago", 
         title = "Deaths",
         xlab = FALSE,
         ylab = "",
         legend = "none",
         repel = TRUE,
         show.line.label = TRUE,
         ggtheme = theme_gray()) +
  scale_x_date(date_breaks = "21 days", date_labels = "%m/%d") +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 100, 10))

g_conf_pop + g_death_pop +
  plot_annotation("COVID-19 Cases & Deaths per 100,000 Population")

br_last <- interest %>% 
  filter(country == "Brazil") %>% 
  slice_tail(n = 1) %>% 
  select(cases_Mpop, deaths_Mpop)

When population is accounted for, Brazils position in comparison to the other countries does not appear as severely negative as the raw counts suggests. In terms of confirmed cases, Brazils total of 517.1835822 is just more than half the value of the United States and Peru. In terms of deaths, Brazils total of 24.1519841 equals the number for Peru but is only one-third less than the number of deaths recorded in the United States and only 30% of the rate of deaths in the UK.

Doubling Time of COVID-19 Deaths

One of the epidemiological indicators that an epidemic is decelerating is an increase in the doubling time of deaths due to the disease. Below is a table of the calculations of the last three doublings of deaths from COVID in Brazil. As can be seen, the doubling time, which had been stable for more than a month is slowing. However, it is important to remember

double_death <- br_data %>% 
  filter(date_d >= date_first_death & reg == "Brasil") %>%
  select(date_d, deaths_accum)

total_deaths <- double_death$deaths_accum[nrow(double_death)]

half_tot_deaths <- floor(total_deaths/2)
quarter_tot_deaths <- floor(half_tot_deaths/2)
eighth_tot_deaths <- floor(quarter_tot_deaths/2)


# Using total deaths of 40919 as of 1106 as current


date_8th <- double_death$date[double_death$deaths_accum > eighth_tot_deaths][1]
date_quart <- double_death$date[double_death$deaths_accum > quarter_tot_deaths][1]
date_half <- double_death$date[double_death$deaths_accum > half_tot_deaths][1]
date_tot <- double_death$date[double_death$deaths_accum == total_deaths][1]

dt_1 <- date_quart - date_8th
dt_2 <- date_half - date_quart
dt_3 <- date_tot - date_half

dt <- tibble(level = c(quarter_tot_deaths, half_tot_deaths, total_deaths),
             dbltime = c(dt_1, dt_2, dt_3))
kable(dt, caption = "COVID-19 Deaths--Doubling Time",
      col.names = c("Level", "Days from Previous Doubling")) %>% 
  kable_styling(full_width = FALSE)

50617 25 days

Conclusion

The COVID-19 pandemic in Brazil is still in its first, ascendant phase. Brazils case load and the resulting deaths have not yet reached their peak. However, the doubling time of deaths indicate that the epidemic is slowing. When the first phase will end is still difficult to say. Part of the problem surrounding predictability of COVID-19 in Brazil is the quality of the data, which I discussed at length above.
